1
00:00:02,274 --> 00:00:13,192
When I'm on a time limit like this, I tend to cut things short and I end up talking about five minutes, so I'm just hoping I can space it out a bit.

2
00:00:13,211 --> 00:00:19,861
I'm just waiting for questions and answers, just in case I finish early, I can fill out.

3
00:00:30,980 --> 00:00:58,253
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambudassam Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambudassam Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hato samma-sambudassam

4
00:00:58,451 --> 00:01:05,085
Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened.

5
00:01:05,105 --> 00:01:19,835
I just wanted to talk about karma and just give you, well for those of you who haven't come across the teachings of the Buddha on that, just to lay the platform and then just see...

6
00:01:20,643 --> 00:01:32,254
as we were saying this morning, how we create suffering for ourselves, how we bring it to an end, and how full liberation is possible, even in this lifetime.

7
00:01:37,599 --> 00:01:47,528
The fundamental law that exists beneath everything is what is termed as the this-that law.

8
00:01:48,503 --> 00:02:18,257
and it's basically a law of causality so we're all I think fairly familiar with the idea of cause and effect that something in the past is causing something in the present and if something doesn't happen in the past something doesn't happen in the present if you don't turn up for work you don't get your wages simple as that so there's both commissions, things that we do and omissions, things that we don't do which have an effect

9
00:02:20,026 --> 00:02:24,012
But the Buddha also pointed out things happen now because things happen now.

10
00:02:24,051 --> 00:02:31,324
It's not only a contingency a sort of connectedness with the past but an absolute connectedness with the present.

11
00:02:32,645 --> 00:02:46,927
So here we have so many people in this room who all and you've all come from a past you all started off from a different place this morning you all made your way here and because that happened I'm able to give this talk.

12
00:02:47,110 --> 00:02:52,014
If it hadn't happened, I'd have had a day off.

13
00:02:52,034 --> 00:02:59,763
So, if you can think of streams of effects coming from the past and meeting, you see.

14
00:03:00,524 --> 00:03:09,473
Now, if everything were just cause and effect from the past, it would suggest a repetitive universe, because where would you find your creativity?

15
00:03:09,573 --> 00:03:10,914
Everything is determined.

16
00:03:11,675 --> 00:03:14,198
And that would lead us to a morality of fate.

17
00:03:14,549 --> 00:03:18,979
things happen, you know, it's in the will of God and all that sort of understanding.

18
00:03:20,944 --> 00:03:29,907
On the other hand, if it were just things happening at present without any connection to the past, you would presume it'd be chaotic because there'd be no order

19
00:03:30,832 --> 00:03:35,819
And that would lead you to a morality where nothing mattered.

20
00:03:35,919 --> 00:03:36,520
What does it matter?

21
00:03:36,920 --> 00:03:49,877
In the Buddha's time, there was one teacher who said, if you went down to one side of the Ganges, murdering, stealing, creating havoc, and came up the other side with great acts of compassion and love, it wouldn't make a blind bit of difference.

22
00:03:51,661 --> 00:03:53,864
Sort of an antinomian world.

23
00:03:53,883 --> 00:03:57,769
So, somehow, the Buddha said there was a connection between these two.

24
00:03:58,389 --> 00:04:00,132
And every moment has both.

25
00:04:00,802 --> 00:04:22,541
a connection with the past and an immediate connection with the present so there's that feeling of an interconnectedness a sort of contingency a touching at all sorts of different levels and we'll come to that in a bit so if you carry that in your mind and what it's telling us is this

26
00:04:22,757 --> 00:04:51,550
we don't know what's going to happen we live in a world where we think we know because generally speaking this room will be here next year but if you look at that law you really don't know what's going to happen next because we don't know what's going to meet at this particular point in time and that leads us if you really contemplate that that leads us to fear

27
00:04:52,846 --> 00:04:55,247
Because one thing the self wants is security.

28
00:04:55,749 --> 00:04:58,211
It wants to know exactly what's happening next year.

29
00:04:58,471 --> 00:05:01,875
Because I want to take my holidays in the south of England.

30
00:05:01,894 --> 00:05:08,060
And the weather forecast is a wonderful attempt at trying to determine what happens.

31
00:05:08,942 --> 00:05:11,283
I mean, I look it up because of the retreats.

32
00:05:11,884 --> 00:05:13,105
And it's amazing.

33
00:05:13,466 --> 00:05:16,408
Seven days before, they're predicting rain on a particular day.

34
00:05:16,949 --> 00:05:18,430
And then the next day, it's not going to be rain.

35
00:05:18,932 --> 00:05:20,192
And then it is going to be rain.

36
00:05:20,473 --> 00:05:21,975
And it's like, forget it.

37
00:05:22,293 --> 00:05:24,877
So one thing they really can predict is what's happening now.

38
00:05:26,459 --> 00:05:31,326
Which is a blessing, because they have satellites.

39
00:05:32,668 --> 00:05:38,797
So you've got this edge, this knife edge of existence.

40
00:05:38,817 --> 00:05:42,461
See, no past, no future, this knife edge of existence.

41
00:05:42,482 --> 00:05:50,494
And when we can begin to recognize that, we get what's known as the wisdom of insecurity.

42
00:05:51,435 --> 00:05:53,319
Which means that you never presume.

43
00:05:53,839 --> 00:05:55,423
You never live on a presumption.

44
00:05:55,442 --> 00:05:57,146
You never live on an expectation.

45
00:05:57,927 --> 00:06:01,814
And this takes away a certain delusiveness about our lives.

46
00:06:01,853 --> 00:06:05,259
Nobody expected this financial crisis.

47
00:06:06,362 --> 00:06:09,326
And it's affected lots of people and continues to do so.

48
00:06:10,117 --> 00:06:16,024
And there was just this blind expectation that the money would just keep growing.

49
00:06:16,586 --> 00:06:18,387
Where else could it go?

50
00:06:19,389 --> 00:06:21,692
It was quite obvious to everybody.

51
00:06:24,415 --> 00:06:32,887
And that edge of insecurity, like we did this morning, is always making us look at the ending of things.

52
00:06:34,088 --> 00:06:36,913
Remember, the self doesn't like insecurity.

53
00:06:37,072 --> 00:06:39,516
So it always presumes something's going to come up.

54
00:06:39,867 --> 00:06:42,812
Something's always going to be there when you jump out of the plane.

55
00:06:43,452 --> 00:06:45,997
You know, like every moment there's always going to be something.

56
00:06:47,117 --> 00:06:50,803
Now that sense of insecurity brings us to the fear of death.

57
00:06:52,105 --> 00:06:55,151
And if you look at all fear, it's the fear of death.

58
00:06:56,252 --> 00:06:57,514
Death here meaning endings.

59
00:06:58,617 --> 00:06:59,517
Death meaning loss.

60
00:06:59,939 --> 00:07:03,985
Death meaning that which we cannot control.

61
00:07:05,163 --> 00:07:05,483
See?

62
00:07:05,824 --> 00:07:20,199
Now, paradoxically, the more we're at home with the feelings of those fear, the fear of death, coming to that wisdom of insecurity, the fears disappear, which means that we can live more fully in the present moment.

63
00:07:22,723 --> 00:07:25,565
That's the benefit you get of losing fear.

64
00:07:27,348 --> 00:07:30,151
Remember, fear has this way of stopping us doing things.

65
00:07:30,170 --> 00:07:33,093
It manifests sometimes in doubt, fear of failure.

66
00:07:33,613 --> 00:07:37,458
So you don't go into a relationship just in case it's not going to work out.

67
00:07:37,478 --> 00:07:39,281
You don't take a job just in case, you see.

68
00:07:39,300 --> 00:07:40,541
It becomes a barrier.

69
00:07:41,863 --> 00:07:48,071
So if you want to hit fear right, if you want to put your head right in the mouth of the lion, see, go towards death.

70
00:07:49,512 --> 00:07:56,000
And when the fear of death has become undermined, all fear becomes undermined.

71
00:07:56,019 --> 00:07:58,642
Now I'm saying this especially because I have a retreat on death.

72
00:07:59,298 --> 00:08:01,079
And you're all welcome.

73
00:08:01,721 --> 00:08:04,624
That's just a little plug.

74
00:08:04,903 --> 00:08:09,589
All the retreats, all the retreats are full, but not this one.

75
00:08:09,610 --> 00:08:13,293
And I can't understand why.

76
00:08:13,834 --> 00:08:15,435
It's such an interesting subject.

77
00:08:15,896 --> 00:08:20,802
Anyway.

78
00:08:20,822 --> 00:08:21,442
So, okay.

79
00:08:21,783 --> 00:08:23,326
So we've got that basic law.

80
00:08:23,826 --> 00:08:24,646
This and that.

81
00:08:25,065 --> 00:08:27,608
Things coming from the past, things happening in the present.

82
00:08:28,088 --> 00:08:30,711
A sense of unknowability about the future.

83
00:08:31,773 --> 00:08:32,634
Not in control.

84
00:08:33,254 --> 00:08:43,725
Now, when it comes to our actions, when it comes to what happens to us, there are five laws.

85
00:08:44,264 --> 00:08:48,249
And this gets rid of these very mechanical ideas about karma.

86
00:08:48,750 --> 00:08:51,832
That if something happens to you, it's because you did something in your past life.

87
00:08:52,082 --> 00:09:15,794
or you did something wrong somewhere in your existence and it's taken eons to come round but it's finally smacked you in the back of the head so the first law is what's known as the law of heat which is basically the physical laws so the physical laws include for us all the laws of physics, of geology, of chemistry

88
00:09:15,995 --> 00:09:17,798
And it's one set of laws.

89
00:09:17,817 --> 00:09:25,951
I mean, if you look at where we're living, you've got all these so-called subatomic laws that govern the subatomic world.

90
00:09:26,393 --> 00:09:28,777
You've got the physical chemical laws on top of that.

91
00:09:29,258 --> 00:09:31,402
You've got the biological laws on top of that.

92
00:09:31,982 --> 00:09:33,966
You've got the psychological laws.

93
00:09:33,985 --> 00:09:35,368
And then you've got the social laws.

94
00:09:36,090 --> 00:09:41,479
And all these laws are somehow interconnected, but they're quite different.

95
00:09:41,677 --> 00:09:47,664
And we live within, I mean, I'm sure there are more, and we live within that mass of contingency.

96
00:09:48,285 --> 00:09:51,529
All these things are touching us.

97
00:09:51,549 --> 00:09:59,460
So, for instance, when this terrible flood happened in Pakistan, was that because in their past lives they drowned so many people?

98
00:10:00,240 --> 00:10:07,811
So, making that sort of very mechanical idea of karma is something the Buddha would not have agreed to.

99
00:10:08,991 --> 00:10:11,414
He said there are all sorts of reasons why things happen.

100
00:10:11,934 --> 00:10:13,076
So there's your first thing.

101
00:10:13,697 --> 00:10:26,717
And it may not be, something might not be caused by you at all, but your karma, and we'll come back to this, is how you react to it.

102
00:10:26,738 --> 00:10:28,019
That's your karma.

103
00:10:29,671 --> 00:10:33,976
Then there are the laws of, yes, biology.

104
00:10:34,336 --> 00:10:50,619
So that's another area where you get, you know, awful, sort of really painful statements where if somebody's born with a disease, you know, a hereditary disease, then it's presumed that sometime in their past life they must have done something terrible.

105
00:10:52,061 --> 00:10:55,826
If you remember, what was his name, the manager of England?

106
00:10:57,148 --> 00:10:57,248
Yeah.

107
00:10:58,797 --> 00:11:27,875
very unfortunate I'm not so sure he meant it but they made him mean it and that really isn't again what the Buddha says because as we know now the body we end up with is caused by who knows what you know hundreds of generations who've misbehaved how could I possibly so you end up with this body because of other reasons but how you relate to your body ah that's something else ok

108
00:11:29,273 --> 00:11:30,815
So you've got all the biological law.

109
00:11:31,615 --> 00:11:38,527
Then you have the laws of psychology, which we're fairly familiar about.

110
00:11:38,547 --> 00:11:39,648
Most people are familiar with those.

111
00:11:39,687 --> 00:11:41,971
How the mind works.

112
00:11:42,111 --> 00:11:49,142
Without going into too much detail, I'll come back to this towards the end because I think this is a crucial understanding.

113
00:11:50,364 --> 00:11:55,010
We are dependent upon our senses to the world that we create.

114
00:11:56,864 --> 00:12:03,274
And in Buddhist understanding, we can't stop information coming in at the level of the senses.

115
00:12:03,335 --> 00:12:04,275
It just comes to us.

116
00:12:05,258 --> 00:12:10,746
And inwardly, things come up as memories, as emotional states.

117
00:12:11,106 --> 00:12:14,732
And all these are conditioned by past behavior or by the world.

118
00:12:16,696 --> 00:12:20,221
Then we have this reaction, this relationship to what is actually happening.

119
00:12:20,489 --> 00:12:22,291
And it's this relationship we've been looking at.

120
00:12:22,751 --> 00:12:23,692
Wanting, not wanting.

121
00:12:24,133 --> 00:12:27,336
We create an attitude towards things.

122
00:12:27,356 --> 00:12:31,101
And again that comes from a deeper misunderstanding as to who we are.

123
00:12:32,583 --> 00:12:35,727
This sense of self.

124
00:12:35,748 --> 00:12:37,210
Then there comes the law of karma.

125
00:12:37,990 --> 00:12:42,395
Now the law of karma is to do with our well-being or lack of it.

126
00:12:42,966 --> 00:13:12,011
and then finally there are the spiritual laws which are to do with the practices that we that we're doing the Pasana practice even the law of karma itself is part of the spiritual laws okay so when you take all when you look at all that you see karma is only this little slot and it's to do with in a very wide sense of that term our ethical behavior okay

127
00:13:13,493 --> 00:13:27,456
So now, if we now look at how we create the world, and this is the Buddhist psychology for those of you who know dependent origination.

128
00:13:28,798 --> 00:13:30,120
So there's contact.

129
00:13:31,462 --> 00:13:37,172
Now, this point of contact is entirely determined by the sense base.

130
00:13:38,384 --> 00:13:43,688
So if a person is colour blind they simply won't see the world the way most other people do.

131
00:13:46,510 --> 00:13:49,975
But even our seeing is particular to us.

132
00:13:51,155 --> 00:14:01,905
So although we all might be looking at the colour blue we'll all see something ever so slightly different.

133
00:14:01,926 --> 00:14:06,429
And I have a very crude tool to express that.

134
00:14:06,570 --> 00:14:07,850
I can only say blue.

135
00:14:08,287 --> 00:14:20,710
I mean, it's obvious when it's light blue or navy blue, but if it's a blue that we all agree with, it's very difficult to express to each other, you know, the shade or the type of blue that we're actually seeing.

136
00:14:22,734 --> 00:14:24,998
So there's a point where words can't communicate.

137
00:14:28,024 --> 00:14:31,509
Now this blue that I'm creating is within my mind.

138
00:14:31,878 --> 00:14:40,450
And as we know from our own psychology, this picture of blue is then thrown out onto what I'm looking at.

139
00:14:42,452 --> 00:14:50,663
So when you've seen these...

140
00:14:51,063 --> 00:14:55,831
Whenever we look at a picture, we see the full frame, the full picture.

141
00:14:56,392 --> 00:15:00,197
But when the eye is actually photographed,

142
00:15:00,328 --> 00:15:01,029
as a film.

143
00:15:01,470 --> 00:15:04,193
It's actually moving all over the place, scanning completely.

144
00:15:04,494 --> 00:15:05,855
And we're completely unaware of that.

145
00:15:06,397 --> 00:15:07,658
Just picking up little pixels.

146
00:15:09,640 --> 00:15:11,703
And that's what the Buddha means by contact, you see.

147
00:15:11,783 --> 00:15:15,187
And it comes into the mind, into the brain-mind complex.

148
00:15:15,469 --> 00:15:18,352
Because the brain and mind in Buddhism are two different energies.

149
00:15:18,373 --> 00:15:20,034
They're not the same.

150
00:15:20,054 --> 00:15:23,379
It comes into there and it begins to be perceived.

151
00:15:23,499 --> 00:15:25,100
It begins to put on a sort of screen.

152
00:15:26,202 --> 00:15:26,302
Yeah?

153
00:15:27,227 --> 00:15:31,693
And this screen then is magically deposited back onto the object.

154
00:15:31,714 --> 00:15:34,577
This we already know from our own psychology.

155
00:15:36,440 --> 00:15:45,392
So can you see that even at the level of something so tangible, something that we see, something that we touch, it's all being internally created.

156
00:15:46,092 --> 00:15:47,615
It's all being internally created.

157
00:15:53,263 --> 00:15:55,125
So this world that we're living in

158
00:15:57,181 --> 00:16:00,163
is just a bubble around me.

159
00:16:00,563 --> 00:16:03,907
The world I'm living in is a bubble around me.

160
00:16:05,109 --> 00:16:07,750
Outside that bubble the world doesn't exist.

161
00:16:12,174 --> 00:16:15,438
And this world that I'm living in is not the same as yours.

162
00:16:17,220 --> 00:16:19,241
It may be very similar but it's not the same.

163
00:16:22,304 --> 00:16:24,167
And you can't enter my world.

164
00:16:25,835 --> 00:16:27,076
and I can't enter yours.

165
00:16:28,977 --> 00:16:31,519
I mean, that's why we have art, isn't it?

166
00:16:31,860 --> 00:16:39,647
Because I have an experience and I want to express it to you I find a medium through which I can get that maybe I can get that across.

167
00:16:47,234 --> 00:16:47,333
Yeah?

168
00:16:47,354 --> 00:16:54,340
In the Buddha's time there wouldn't have made a distinction between the world and consciousness.

169
00:16:54,876 --> 00:16:55,879
The world and self.

170
00:16:56,799 --> 00:16:59,785
Self, consciousness and the world were all the same thing.

171
00:17:02,450 --> 00:17:06,257
It was understood at that time that the world was always completely subjective.

172
00:17:08,400 --> 00:17:10,865
In our own culture, we objectified it.

173
00:17:12,508 --> 00:17:17,195
I think it crystallised somewhere around the 18th century, our enlightenment.

174
00:17:17,215 --> 00:17:18,438
I'll say that twice.

175
00:17:18,458 --> 00:17:19,720
Our enlightenment.

176
00:17:20,375 --> 00:17:23,479
And in objectifying the world like that, it gave us control.

177
00:17:24,038 --> 00:17:25,099
We began to control it.

178
00:17:25,240 --> 00:17:27,923
And that's where we get our wonderful science and technology.

179
00:17:29,305 --> 00:17:37,755
But then we entered into this delusion that actually we are all experiencing an objective world.

180
00:17:37,775 --> 00:17:42,160
And I believe only now neurobiology is telling us that in fact we're not.

181
00:17:42,559 --> 00:17:46,805
We are experiencing the world as we can only experience it.

182
00:17:47,025 --> 00:17:48,626
There is no objective world.

183
00:17:50,917 --> 00:17:51,398
There isn't one.

184
00:17:52,921 --> 00:17:55,564
When I say there isn't one, I mean from experience.

185
00:17:55,584 --> 00:17:59,528
It doesn't mean to say that when we all leave this room, this building disappears.

186
00:18:00,891 --> 00:18:04,295
That would be an idealism, wouldn't it?

187
00:18:04,315 --> 00:18:08,779
To be is to be perceived.

188
00:18:08,799 --> 00:18:10,382
But you can see the logic in that.

189
00:18:11,463 --> 00:18:17,971
You'll find that certain schools of Buddhism towards the Mahayana actually came to that form of idealism.

190
00:18:19,842 --> 00:18:25,089
But the Buddha didn't go that far to say that everything is created through mind.

191
00:18:26,732 --> 00:18:34,044
The Buddha is very grounded in what is it that we can know, rather than speculate on.

192
00:18:34,064 --> 00:18:45,241
So, for instance, with, if I remember rightly, the philosopher Barclay, Bishop Barclay, when he argued very strongly that to be is to be perceived, and this is what we're actually saying, in a sense, hmm?

193
00:18:46,048 --> 00:18:49,071
When he was asked, how does everything else exist when you can't perceive it?

194
00:18:49,231 --> 00:18:50,313
Well, it's in the mind of God.

195
00:18:50,854 --> 00:18:51,673
See?

196
00:18:52,115 --> 00:18:55,417
That's an easy way out, that.

197
00:18:55,438 --> 00:18:59,342
So, the Buddha, having declared that there wasn't a God, is stuck.

198
00:19:00,202 --> 00:19:03,066
I'll sort of go there.

199
00:19:04,646 --> 00:19:14,757
So, the Buddha is very careful not to enter into anything which is of that sort of transcendental sort.

200
00:19:14,737 --> 00:19:22,265
that sort of thinking he doesn't go there so he doesn't ask all those questions that we'd love to ask like why am I here?

201
00:19:24,788 --> 00:19:28,251
he's only answering the question you are here, how is it you're suffering?

202
00:19:33,657 --> 00:19:44,170
so if we can now imagine that we are in this bubble and the edges of this bubble are in contact with things that come towards it

203
00:19:45,027 --> 00:19:46,589
And it has these senses.

204
00:19:46,690 --> 00:19:51,098
It sees, it touches, it smells, it tastes, and so on.

205
00:19:52,962 --> 00:19:55,888
At that point, we bring this stuff in, okay?

206
00:19:55,909 --> 00:19:56,671
And it's perceived.

207
00:19:58,493 --> 00:20:06,309
Now, there's something happens inside the bubble, which is our relationship to what we're experiencing, okay?

208
00:20:06,913 --> 00:20:11,845
And that relationship is either we're saying to ourselves, this is fantastic.

209
00:20:13,067 --> 00:20:13,829
And you want to hold it.

210
00:20:14,391 --> 00:20:15,452
And you want to develop it.

211
00:20:15,532 --> 00:20:17,096
You want to find out how you can get more of it.

212
00:20:18,279 --> 00:20:19,382
Or you're saying, I don't want this.

213
00:20:19,942 --> 00:20:21,026
And you're trying to push it out.

214
00:20:21,046 --> 00:20:22,127
Trying to push it out of the bubble.

215
00:20:22,348 --> 00:20:23,029
Trying to get rid of it.

216
00:20:24,513 --> 00:20:24,634
Yeah?

217
00:20:24,653 --> 00:20:24,753
Yeah?

218
00:20:25,830 --> 00:20:38,509
So this duality of wanting and not wanting, of acquiring, of being in conflict, and of course the other side of aversion is that if something's in the bubble that we don't like, then of course try and run from it.

219
00:20:39,830 --> 00:20:42,634
Try and turn away from it, find a little hiding place.

220
00:20:42,654 --> 00:20:43,936
Or stamp it down somewhere.

221
00:20:44,257 --> 00:20:47,821
Put it under a heavy load.

222
00:20:49,320 --> 00:20:54,128
And every time we react that way, we create a conditioning.

223
00:20:54,288 --> 00:20:57,753
This conditioning is simply, when this comes, this is the way I react.

224
00:21:00,598 --> 00:21:08,652
So if I find that somebody has given me a chocolate, and I put it on my mouth and I think, ooh, that's very nice.

225
00:21:08,672 --> 00:21:12,678
And there comes this relationship with this piece of chocolate.

226
00:21:12,698 --> 00:21:16,324
I then think to myself, that would be nice to have some more of that.

227
00:21:17,704 --> 00:21:23,772
And all the time, by doing that, I'm creating a relationship with chocolate.

228
00:21:23,792 --> 00:21:28,199
Now, this relationship with chocolate is creating within me an atmosphere.

229
00:21:29,381 --> 00:21:31,163
This atmosphere I call happiness.

230
00:21:33,205 --> 00:21:36,971
And it's not the chocolate so much that I want, is it?

231
00:21:37,151 --> 00:21:38,532
But the happiness that it creates.

232
00:21:40,695 --> 00:21:43,759
So now this happiness is dependent on chocolate.

233
00:21:45,201 --> 00:21:45,702
It's crazy.

234
00:21:47,741 --> 00:21:54,111
And if I look at all my happinesses they're always dependent on something over which I can't control.

235
00:21:56,034 --> 00:21:58,778
The worst is other human beings.

236
00:22:03,203 --> 00:22:04,967
You cannot trust another human being.

237
00:22:06,669 --> 00:22:07,631
They're generally horrible.

238
00:22:08,372 --> 00:22:11,175
And worse than that, they die.

239
00:22:11,936 --> 00:22:16,163
I mean, just when you've got this love relationship the person disappears.

240
00:22:20,142 --> 00:22:32,954
So that relationship we have with things coming in, you see, with things beautiful coming in, that are creating this beautiful internal space, always have the potential of making us unhappy.

241
00:22:34,616 --> 00:22:42,544
But there's more, because we now become addicted to what's there, and we start doing things to really maintain it.

242
00:22:43,404 --> 00:22:45,086
And that leads us to...

243
00:22:45,691 --> 00:22:50,096
Immoral action, meaning that we're doing things which are actually harmful.

244
00:22:50,115 --> 00:22:52,058
Harmful to ourselves and harmful to others.

245
00:22:53,961 --> 00:23:01,410
I can't remember his name now, but a bank robber in America was asked, why does he rob banks?

246
00:23:01,990 --> 00:23:06,015
And he said, because that's where the money is.

247
00:23:06,796 --> 00:23:06,955
See?

248
00:23:07,777 --> 00:23:10,680
What's the problem?

249
00:23:10,721 --> 00:23:12,001
That's where the money is.

250
00:23:13,720 --> 00:23:19,608
So you see, we get into such a corner that money means happiness and it's in banks.

251
00:23:20,309 --> 00:23:20,971
So what's the problem?

252
00:23:20,990 --> 00:23:21,491
You don't get it.

253
00:23:24,836 --> 00:23:28,383
On the other side you've got all the negativity.

254
00:23:29,144 --> 00:23:35,614
So something comes into consciousness, we don't like it and we form a negativity, a resistance.

255
00:23:36,434 --> 00:23:41,482
If that's too much if that discomfort is too much

256
00:23:41,580 --> 00:23:45,707
then we start moving towards an antagonism.

257
00:23:46,008 --> 00:23:51,076
The aversion moves into a real irritation, an anger, a frustration.

258
00:23:51,355 --> 00:23:53,700
It moves into a deep-seated hate.

259
00:23:54,942 --> 00:24:06,660
Very quickly you can move across the whole gamut of human horror in just relating wrongly to something that we're perceiving is actually causing me unhappiness.

260
00:24:06,826 --> 00:24:09,250
So, this comes in, you see.

261
00:24:09,830 --> 00:24:13,176
Somebody says something like, you know, you stupid bald-headed monk.

262
00:24:13,979 --> 00:24:14,358
Possibly.

263
00:24:17,625 --> 00:24:20,309
You see, these words have stopped here, you see.

264
00:24:20,710 --> 00:24:23,736
And the emotion, the hatred, stopped here.

265
00:24:24,436 --> 00:24:25,238
It didn't come any further.

266
00:24:25,258 --> 00:24:27,261
That's the surface of my bubble, you see.

267
00:24:27,803 --> 00:24:29,065
But, of course, I'm incensed.

268
00:24:29,486 --> 00:24:30,166
I mean, how could...

269
00:24:30,568 --> 00:24:53,910
how could anybody say that to me so I take it in and these words are there within my within they're resonating around and my reaction is I'm getting angry is it and then I say to myself hold on I'm a monk I better not do that I suffer down I suffer down cool down cool down and then while I'm having a cup of tea

270
00:24:54,093 --> 00:25:16,252
all these are coming from past experiences to anything that I experience as being unpleasant and remember the unpleasantness stops here at the feeling level the unpleasantness I feel within me is being caused by me as a reaction

271
00:25:16,434 --> 00:25:24,942
So I find that my anger is making me unhappy and if I can't do anything about my anger I push it down, I get depressed, all that sort of stuff.

272
00:25:25,125 --> 00:25:32,232
And if the enemy, if I experience the enemy as too great, then it begins to build up this internal atmosphere of fear.

273
00:25:33,493 --> 00:25:35,455
And that fear I find very difficult to be with.

274
00:25:36,217 --> 00:25:42,923
I push it away, I run away, I do anything just to get away from this outer stimulus.

275
00:25:44,005 --> 00:25:51,432
But remember, all these outer stimuli are not actually creating this business inside.

276
00:25:52,272 --> 00:25:54,255
That's the crucial understanding.

277
00:25:54,386 --> 00:25:57,150
nobody can cause us psychological pain.

278
00:25:59,712 --> 00:26:02,455
You have to really sort of grasp that point.

279
00:26:02,476 --> 00:26:04,657
Nobody can cause us psychological pain.

280
00:26:05,278 --> 00:26:06,640
It's all being produced by us.

281
00:26:07,580 --> 00:26:11,105
Discomfort, yes, I mean, I hear the words, I hear that, but that's nothing.

282
00:26:11,605 --> 00:26:19,273
The internal stuff that comes up, the turmoil, the addictions, all that, are caused by me, inside.

283
00:26:20,315 --> 00:26:20,394
See?

284
00:26:22,720 --> 00:26:34,636
So here we have this little bubble, you see, and I'm creating this world inside and that's what the Buddha means by karma when it comes to the karma of liberation.

285
00:26:34,698 --> 00:26:36,442
This is the karma he's talking about.

286
00:26:37,115 --> 00:26:46,686
This is where his whole teaching is centred on how to turn this internal life into a way which brings us towards happiness.

287
00:26:46,707 --> 00:26:52,375
Now that happiness is not, remember, to be confused with Nibbana, may come to that at the end.

288
00:26:53,055 --> 00:26:56,299
It's basically trying to clear up our ethical lives.

289
00:26:58,041 --> 00:27:06,732
Because what we find is that my relationship to the world is always being governed by liking, not liking, wanting, not wanting.

290
00:27:07,625 --> 00:27:36,821
the liking not liking is a given you can't stop that that's part of the perceptual process we can see when something tastes and it doesn't taste nice that's not a problem it's the not wanting it it's the internal reaction which is causing the internal atmosphere of disgust or whatever it is yeah once you've clicked into that you see first of all it's incredibly disappointing

291
00:27:37,342 --> 00:27:39,444
Because from now on you can't blame anybody.

292
00:27:41,167 --> 00:27:42,430
Nobody can make you unhappy.

293
00:27:42,450 --> 00:27:44,673
I mean, it's not right, is it?

294
00:27:47,858 --> 00:27:53,207
On the other hand, it now gives you total power over your own well-being.

295
00:27:54,630 --> 00:28:00,638
When you realise that actually your well-being is not determined by what's outside of it.

296
00:28:00,659 --> 00:28:02,803
So, let's take this financial crisis.

297
00:28:02,962 --> 00:28:04,345
Many people are going to suffer.

298
00:28:05,117 --> 00:28:08,903
suffer loss of job, loss of income, all that sort of stuff.

299
00:28:08,923 --> 00:28:10,183
That's bad enough in itself.

300
00:28:11,346 --> 00:28:23,500
But there then comes the internal suffering of the loss of status, the loss of what money would normally bring, and the anger about that, and then the depression about that.

301
00:28:23,941 --> 00:28:30,048
All that is not directly caused by the situation, by this person's internal reaction to it.

302
00:28:31,611 --> 00:28:34,855
And society would generally say that was justified

303
00:28:35,424 --> 00:28:40,269
So everybody now feels that unless they are angry about the situation, something's wrong.

304
00:28:40,810 --> 00:28:41,632
Something's wrong with them.

305
00:28:42,272 --> 00:28:42,792
They ought to be.

306
00:28:42,813 --> 00:28:44,515
They ought to go out and kill somebody.

307
00:28:45,336 --> 00:28:49,279
That's the only way to really bring justice to the world.

308
00:28:50,321 --> 00:28:59,270
So what the society is telling us is that there's no way that you can be at peace with the situation as it is.

309
00:29:00,553 --> 00:29:00,673
Right?

310
00:29:01,278 --> 00:29:30,238
but when you realize that that isn't necessary that all that all that internal anger and all that stuff isn't necessary then what that does is liberate you it liberates you to actually work with the situation as it is the other negativity is drawing energy it's drawing energy away from you and it's throwing it out more bad energy whereas when something happens like this financial crisis

311
00:29:30,538 --> 00:29:42,895
if it only stops at the point of economic pain, it is pain, then there's this liberation inside, there's this freedom inside to work with the situation.

312
00:29:43,797 --> 00:29:46,540
He doesn't mean to say that we don't go and hang some of these bangers.

313
00:29:47,803 --> 00:29:51,828
There's got to be justice somewhere.

314
00:29:52,849 --> 00:29:57,896
What I'm saying is that the internal horror is not necessary here.

315
00:29:58,348 --> 00:30:03,144
I mean, the whole point of a judge is that he doesn't get angry.

316
00:30:03,596 --> 00:30:06,661
He's not supposed to sit up there and say, you, how could you do that?

317
00:30:07,321 --> 00:30:08,963
I'll have you hanged.

318
00:30:09,545 --> 00:30:14,250
He's supposed to remain calm, not get involved with the emotions of the lawyers.

319
00:30:14,270 --> 00:30:17,094
He's not supposed to be confused by their clever arguments.

320
00:30:17,474 --> 00:30:20,077
He's not supposed to be prejudiced and all that.

321
00:30:20,097 --> 00:30:26,306
So we expect these very clear attitudes of a judge.

322
00:30:27,007 --> 00:30:30,111
But we don't expect it of ourselves.

323
00:30:30,614 --> 00:30:39,307
So now, once we've clicked into that understanding that we are creating our own suffering, then that's a liberation for us.

324
00:30:39,327 --> 00:30:40,730
Okay, that's a liberation for us.

325
00:30:40,750 --> 00:30:42,313
Because now we can take control.

326
00:30:43,394 --> 00:30:49,065
And what we find is, of course, that working with it is not easy.

327
00:30:49,424 --> 00:30:55,895
Because as soon as we sit, the old habits, these old habits have enormous momentum, right?

328
00:30:56,365 --> 00:31:09,041
But the other thing about recognizing that the outside world or what is happening to us on the outside is not the direct cause, the catalyst, but it's not a direct cause for our internal stuff.

329
00:31:10,984 --> 00:31:13,468
It means that...

330
00:31:13,488 --> 00:31:17,133
Hold on, I've lost my train of thought there.

331
00:31:17,153 --> 00:31:17,973
It's gone.

332
00:31:17,993 --> 00:31:19,957
So I'll move on to the next thing.

333
00:31:19,977 --> 00:31:20,617
So...

334
00:31:20,986 --> 00:31:30,619
When we realise that we are in control of this life, it gives us the ability to work with it internally.

335
00:31:31,401 --> 00:31:34,224
And that's what the meditation is about.

336
00:31:34,244 --> 00:31:35,066
And... Oh, that was it.

337
00:31:35,105 --> 00:31:35,886
That's the point.

338
00:31:35,906 --> 00:31:38,170
Come back around the other side.

339
00:31:39,092 --> 00:31:48,003
So the actual anger we feel towards something, or the fear we feel towards something, is, I would say, never appropriate.

340
00:31:48,025 --> 00:31:49,086
Never appropriate.

341
00:31:49,960 --> 00:31:58,773
Because what there is, is a conditioning of anger, is a conditioning of fear and all the rest of it, and a conditioning of excitement and lust and all that sort of stuff.

342
00:31:59,214 --> 00:32:00,978
So there's this conditioning, okay?

343
00:32:02,740 --> 00:32:03,801
It's like a potential.

344
00:32:04,683 --> 00:32:12,896
And if you imagine it like a balloon, and something that pinpricks that balloon, all the energy in that balloon wants to go out through that little hole.

345
00:32:13,585 --> 00:32:16,028
And that's what happens when something makes us angry.

346
00:32:16,729 --> 00:32:18,711
When something makes us despair.

347
00:32:19,372 --> 00:32:21,413
When something makes us excited.

348
00:32:22,595 --> 00:32:30,304
All that conditioning wants to express itself through that particular stimulus.

349
00:32:30,324 --> 00:32:36,951
And that's where we also begin to recognize that the stimulus is not actually causing the mental states.

350
00:32:37,051 --> 00:32:38,292
It's coming from somewhere else.

351
00:32:40,400 --> 00:32:42,683
Then we're left with the karmic results.

352
00:32:42,763 --> 00:32:49,454
I'm using karma here to mean the way we normally use it, like your consequences.

353
00:32:49,955 --> 00:32:55,243
The actual word karma means an action and the proper word for result is vipāda.

354
00:32:55,263 --> 00:32:56,046
We'll put that aside.

355
00:32:57,288 --> 00:33:01,374
Karma, our karma here now, we can't get rid of it.

356
00:33:01,694 --> 00:33:06,001
You can't just stick it in the bin and they'll take it away from us.

357
00:33:05,981 --> 00:33:11,491
It's just stuck within the whole machination of our psyche.

358
00:33:11,511 --> 00:33:15,778
And when you open up to yourself, that's what you come in contact with.

359
00:33:15,818 --> 00:33:18,784
These very strong habitual tendencies.

360
00:33:18,943 --> 00:33:20,446
The Buddha called them tendencies.

361
00:33:20,765 --> 00:33:26,412
In a sense, it's almost like, you know, we would talk about the subconscious, but it's not a thing.

362
00:33:26,511 --> 00:33:28,233
It's not as though it exists.

363
00:33:28,253 --> 00:33:29,875
It's more in the sense of a potential.

364
00:33:30,777 --> 00:33:39,548
A bit more like a computer which holds these programs, but you've got to press a certain command and it manifests.

365
00:33:39,567 --> 00:33:43,092
And the awful thing is that we don't know how much of this stuff there is down there.

366
00:33:43,571 --> 00:33:45,674
We don't know ourselves in that way.

367
00:33:46,211 --> 00:33:59,549
So every time something happens and the stuff comes up, some anger, some depression, some anxiety, whatever it is, you see, that's an opportunity for us to just sit quietly with it, be with it, and allow it to express itself.

368
00:33:59,569 --> 00:34:03,734
And that's what we begin to recognize is the process of healing.

369
00:34:04,415 --> 00:34:10,844
That's where we recognize that this is the way that the heart has to empty itself, right?

370
00:34:10,885 --> 00:34:13,148
These things have to be, in a sense, liberated.

371
00:34:13,869 --> 00:34:16,413
And they have to be done into consciousness.

372
00:34:17,173 --> 00:34:20,498
So that is what he means by suffering our karma.

373
00:34:20,797 --> 00:34:22,320
This is the quality of patience.

374
00:34:22,420 --> 00:34:24,021
Patient forbearance.

375
00:34:24,882 --> 00:34:28,126
Which he says is the highest form of ascetic practice.

376
00:34:28,146 --> 00:34:30,188
And we learn it mainly within ourselves.

377
00:34:31,190 --> 00:34:34,695
Never mind other people and kids.

378
00:34:34,715 --> 00:34:41,041
But we learn it by sitting within ourselves and bearing with the stuff that's coming up.

379
00:34:42,710 --> 00:34:49,317
Now, if it were just that, it might be just an ordinary psychotherapy, you know, just an ordinary healing process.

380
00:34:49,836 --> 00:34:58,945
But what turns it into a spiritual process is beginning to recognize the mechanisms by which it's created, which is this wanting-not-wanting.

381
00:34:58,965 --> 00:35:08,715
And to know that if we just stay with the wanting-not-wanting and let it drain its energy, that particular conditioning is exhausting itself.

382
00:35:08,735 --> 00:35:10,016
That's how it comes to an end.

383
00:35:12,172 --> 00:35:20,583
And when we look at it as something which is impermanent, something which is constantly changing, it helps us to disidentify with it.

384
00:35:22,166 --> 00:35:26,592
And that position of the observer is a transcendent position.

385
00:35:27,353 --> 00:35:28,153
See, consider that.

386
00:35:28,815 --> 00:35:38,387
When you've found that observation post within yourself, everything that you would normally say was mean has now become an object that you're experiencing, but it's still an object.

387
00:35:38,806 --> 00:35:40,829
So the pain in the knee, the pain in the back,

388
00:35:41,097 --> 00:35:50,672
the emotional state that arises, a thought, thoughts are difficult to catch, I'll be a bit more on the point, but images, images, they're all objects to be seen.

389
00:35:51,494 --> 00:35:57,282
So there's something which is separated out from that process and found a perch, you see.

390
00:35:57,864 --> 00:36:07,458
Now when you find that perch in yourself and you're very clearly within yourself, the observer, just try to reflect on that state.

391
00:36:07,961 --> 00:36:15,952
What's it like being that rather than these emotional selves and physical selves?

392
00:36:15,972 --> 00:36:22,161
And the Buddha says that those who are mindful, and that's what he's talking about, those who are mindful are in the presence of Nibbana.

393
00:36:22,181 --> 00:36:24,425
They're in the vicinity of Nibbana.

394
00:36:24,445 --> 00:36:28,170
So we're actually very close to some sort of deep recognition.

395
00:36:29,813 --> 00:36:36,061
Now as we sit in that place of the observer and that very strong sense of self is there,

396
00:36:36,159 --> 00:36:38,583
the self-awareness, the self-awareness.

397
00:36:40,264 --> 00:36:44,050
Normally speaking, people might say, well, this is my sense of presence.

398
00:36:44,731 --> 00:36:45,612
This is what I am.

399
00:36:47,114 --> 00:36:48,476
But it's an object also, isn't it?

400
00:36:48,835 --> 00:36:51,018
You're aware of this sense of self.

401
00:36:52,101 --> 00:36:52,721
So you can't be.

402
00:36:52,760 --> 00:36:55,063
Anything you're aware of, you can't be.

403
00:36:57,847 --> 00:37:04,817
But even so, that place that we found is crucial in terms of our investigation.

404
00:37:05,759 --> 00:37:11,766
And the investigation that the Buddha presents to us is not finding out what there is, but finding out what we're not.

405
00:37:13,108 --> 00:37:15,710
So it's a bit like walking backwards to the edge of a cliff.

406
00:37:16,713 --> 00:37:20,858
We can only hope that when we fall off, something wonderful is awaiting us.

407
00:37:21,659 --> 00:37:27,666
If you turn around on that sense of self, all you get is more senses of self.

408
00:37:29,231 --> 00:37:39,063
So there comes a point where that sense of self disappears just because of the one-pointedness of your attention.

409
00:37:41,045 --> 00:37:49,775
Now it happens, actually, in a wrong way when we get lost in DVDs and films and conversations.

410
00:37:49,795 --> 00:37:52,239
When you are watching a DVD, you wake up, don't you?

411
00:37:52,259 --> 00:37:53,079
An hour or two later.

412
00:37:54,400 --> 00:37:55,121
Where have you been?

413
00:37:55,574 --> 00:37:56,755
There's been no sense of self.

414
00:37:56,956 --> 00:37:58,117
Time has disappeared.

415
00:37:58,577 --> 00:37:59,679
Sense of self has disappeared.

416
00:38:01,199 --> 00:38:02,422
It's a bit like sleep too.

417
00:38:03,302 --> 00:38:06,425
You fall asleep and then you wake up and here I am.

418
00:38:06,445 --> 00:38:07,407
The bell goes and you wake up.

419
00:38:07,967 --> 00:38:08,467
I'm here again.

420
00:38:09,108 --> 00:38:10,050
Where were you?

421
00:38:10,070 --> 00:38:10,791
Where were you in sleep?

422
00:38:12,112 --> 00:38:21,563
That loss of identity into what we're doing unfortunately has been empowered by the desire for happiness.

423
00:38:22,003 --> 00:38:23,505
Seeking happiness in films.

424
00:38:24,277 --> 00:38:28,003
Seeking happiness in food, in conversation, seeking happiness.

425
00:38:28,023 --> 00:38:33,873
So all we do is engender a conditioning of seeking that happiness there.

426
00:38:35,936 --> 00:38:36,637
That's the karma.

427
00:38:37,177 --> 00:38:38,800
That's what Buddha talks about, his karma.

428
00:38:41,164 --> 00:38:49,898
And all we're trying to do is to re-enter the world, re-enter situations, but without that sense of wanting, not wanting.

429
00:38:50,958 --> 00:39:01,335
So, this is where that crucial point on the dependent origination, the weird dependent origination, the crucial point of intention, right, comes into its own.

430
00:39:01,355 --> 00:39:04,760
Because intention is the beginning of karma.

431
00:39:04,780 --> 00:39:10,730
And intention arises, and at that point, all it is, is some idea laced with desire.

432
00:39:11,329 --> 00:39:12,391
Nothing's been activated.

433
00:39:13,172 --> 00:39:14,355
Yeah?

434
00:39:14,375 --> 00:39:16,659
T. See?

435
00:39:16,679 --> 00:39:17,320
Nothing yet.

436
00:39:18,481 --> 00:39:19,362
Just comes up tea.

437
00:39:19,643 --> 00:39:21,967
But before I know it, I'm making tea.

438
00:39:22,126 --> 00:39:23,550
I've drunk it and I don't even know I've done it.

439
00:39:23,949 --> 00:39:25,733
So it's just like tea.

440
00:39:26,034 --> 00:39:35,289
If I can be awake at that moment, I can feel the power of that energy coming up from this balloon we talked about.

441
00:39:35,309 --> 00:39:36,092
It's got a little hole.

442
00:39:36,132 --> 00:39:37,454
It wants to get up there through tea.

443
00:39:38,615 --> 00:39:39,257
Desire.

444
00:39:40,148 --> 00:39:46,574
If we can stay there and just let it go, let that energy go, something has been deflated from that balloon.

445
00:39:47,496 --> 00:39:50,239
Something's gone out of that balloon.

446
00:39:50,259 --> 00:39:53,222
That's the process of purification.

447
00:39:53,242 --> 00:39:59,869
In seeing that, we also recognize that we created it and we can uncreate it.

448
00:40:00,590 --> 00:40:01,831
That's where our choice lies.

449
00:40:01,851 --> 00:40:09,800
That's where our power lies, is to allow things to exhaust themselves and return the heart back to its original purity.

450
00:40:10,878 --> 00:40:39,922
so there are these two lines in terms of the process of liberation there's the process of purification of the heart which we've been talking about which is recognising that we are creating our own internal suffering our own psychological pain and that there are ways in which we can allow this to exhaust itself and this leads us to purity

451
00:40:40,746 --> 00:40:58,079
it began at a point of innocence there's a point in we can't say in time but there's a point beneath our existence which is innocence meaning we never meant to do harm then there comes this crucial moment of an identity

452
00:40:58,583 --> 00:41:04,768
So, coming into every being, like the baby being born, what do they identify with?

453
00:41:04,809 --> 00:41:06,110
You identify with your body.

454
00:41:06,670 --> 00:41:09,132
You identify with your emotions, with your thought patterns.

455
00:41:09,614 --> 00:41:12,577
You identify with people around you.

456
00:41:12,597 --> 00:41:17,541
This identity congregates around a concept that we call the self.

457
00:41:18,722 --> 00:41:23,226
And this self is now trying to manipulate the world to make itself happy.

458
00:41:25,389 --> 00:41:27,931
So, so long as we see these characteristics,

459
00:41:28,181 --> 00:41:32,527
We're undermining this fundamental mistake of who we actually are.

460
00:41:33,788 --> 00:41:49,405
And so that process is a dual process, quite clear in the Buddha's teaching, of insight, driven by this vipassana, began with ignorance, a simple not knowing, not culpable, but then there was the mistake of identity.

461
00:41:50,047 --> 00:41:55,253
And this identity of self, seeking happiness in the world, creates misery and mayhem.

462
00:41:55,688 --> 00:41:59,793
wakes up to its horror and begins the process of devolution.

463
00:42:01,574 --> 00:42:08,242
As it processes devolution it begins to see where the problem lies and it's in these three characteristics.

464
00:42:08,262 --> 00:42:17,172
The role of desire, seeing permanence where there's impermanence and seeing substantiality, self, where there isn't any.

465
00:42:17,192 --> 00:42:25,661
And it leads us to insights which undermine this mistake and takes us back to our original position

466
00:42:26,030 --> 00:42:55,041
but this time with wisdom so we know who we are the Buddha knows who he is and he's not a self running concurrent with that is the product of that delusion which is all the karmic stuff we've got inside that's the karma of liberation through the process of purifying the heart it becomes immaculate so it began at the point of innocence created havoc and mayhem

467
00:42:55,914 --> 00:42:58,878
goes back on the process and returns to purity.

468
00:42:59,338 --> 00:43:10,291
That's why, in the end, and it's not possible, psychologically speaking, for human beings not to become fully liberated.

469
00:43:10,311 --> 00:43:11,132
He never states that.

470
00:43:11,152 --> 00:43:11,552
That's me.

471
00:43:13,755 --> 00:43:17,159
Because if he'd have said that, he'd have been called an eternalist.

472
00:43:18,320 --> 00:43:22,344
But when you see this psychology, you see it's not possible for...

473
00:43:22,831 --> 00:43:49,193
for sentient beings not eventually to liberate themselves and the goal which is driving that liberation is suffering is what the Buddha said what drives us to the end of suffering is suffering itself and so these two are always concurrent with every purification of the heart there arises some insight with every insight there arises some purification of the heart

474
00:43:50,405 --> 00:43:56,376
So that's why when a person becomes liberated he is also ethically beautiful.

475
00:44:01,967 --> 00:44:11,367
It would have been disappointing if the Buddha had been caught shoplifting.

476
00:44:12,510 --> 00:44:17,766
I can only hope my words have not added to your confusion.

477
00:44:17,786 --> 00:44:19,612
Would have clarified the situation.

478
00:44:20,434 --> 00:44:27,735
And that with your constant endeavor you will attain full liberation sooner rather than later.

479
00:44:28,710 --> 00:44:33,438
And you're supposed to say, Sadhu, Sadhu, Sadhu.

480
00:44:33,458 --> 00:44:33,858
Sadhu, Sadhu, Sadhu.

481
00:44:33,878 --> 00:44:37,603
And if you don't say that, you see, I get depressed.

482
00:44:38,646 --> 00:44:46,077
There are scriptures where the listeners delighted in the words of the Buddha, and there are others where they were silent.

483
00:44:48,760 --> 00:44:52,085
So I have to bring it to an end there, because we have to get out by five o'clock.

